---
/**
 * Studio About Page
 * Explains the method and purpose
 */

import StudioLayout from '../../studio/StudioLayout.astro';
---

<StudioLayout title="About Studio" palette="noir" motion="subtle">
  <article class="about">
    <header class="about-header">
      <h1 class="about-title">About Studio</h1>
      <p class="about-subtitle">On method and purpose</p>
    </header>

    <div class="about-content studio-prose">
      <section>
        <h2>What This Is</h2>
        <p>
          Studio is a space for slow thinking. Each essay is a conceptual territory—
          explored through argument, illustration, and interaction.
        </p>
        <p>
          Unlike typical blog posts, these essays use motion and interaction to 
          clarify structure. Margin notes provide tangential thoughts without 
          disrupting the main argument. Footnotes expand inline rather than 
          breaking your reading flow. Pull quotes emphasize key ideas.
        </p>
        <p>
          This is philosophy as practice: rigorous, visual, built to be inhabited.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Design Principles</h2>
        
        <h3>1. Motion Serves Meaning</h3>
        <p>
          Every animation has a purpose: to reveal structure, guide attention, 
          or illustrate change. Nothing is decorative. If motion doesn't clarify 
          the argument, it's removed.
        </p>

        <h3>2. Typography First</h3>
        <p>
          Type is the primary interface. The design prioritizes readability: 
          generous line spacing, literary scale, high contrast. Serif for body 
          text, sans-serif for UI elements.
        </p>

        <h3>3. Progressive Enhancement</h3>
        <p>
          The landing page ships zero JavaScript. Essay pages load minimal JS 
          only for interactive features. Everything degrades gracefully. 
          Reduced-motion preferences are respected.
        </p>

        <h3>4. Aesthetic Restraint</h3>
        <p>
          Dark by default. Low contrast, high legibility. Each essay can define 
          its own palette, but the core remains consistent. Nothing flashy. 
          Nothing that distracts from the ideas.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Technical Stack</h2>
        <p>
          Built with <a href="https://astro.build">Astro</a> for static generation. 
          Essays are written in MDX, allowing custom components alongside prose. 
          The design system uses CSS custom properties in an isolated layer—no 
          global styles leak in.
        </p>
        <p>
          Each essay defines its own frontmatter: palette, motion profile, 
          optional ambient audio. The template handles the rest.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Writing for Studio</h2>
        <p>
          Essays here are conceptual, not personal. They explore ideas through 
          argument and illustration. The writing is clear, the structure 
          deliberate. Every sentence earns its place.
        </p>
        <p>
          Topics range from design to philosophy to technical systems—anything 
          that benefits from slow, careful thinking. The common thread is rigor 
          and visual clarity.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Interaction Vocabulary</h2>
        <p>
          Studio essays use a small set of interactive patterns:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li>
            <strong>Margin Notes:</strong> Appear on hover (desktop) or inline 
            (mobile). For tangential thoughts that don't belong in the main flow.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Footnotes:</strong> Expand inline when clicked. Preserve 
            reading flow while providing deeper context.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Pull Quotes:</strong> Emphasize key ideas. Used sparingly 
            to mark conceptual milestones.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Interactive Blocks:</strong> Custom visualizations that 
            illustrate concepts. Only when static text isn't enough.
          </li>
          <li>
            <strong>Ambient Audio:</strong> Optional. Muted by default. Creates 
            atmosphere without demanding attention.
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>On Separation</h2>
        <p>
          Studio is deliberately separate from the main site. It has its own 
          layout, design system, and aesthetic. The only connection is a small 
          footer link.
        </p>
        <p>
          This separation is intentional. The main site serves one purpose; 
          Studio serves another. They don't need to look related. The shift in 
          aesthetic signals a shift in mode: from portfolio to laboratory, 
          from showcase to workshop.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>Get in Touch</h2>
        <p>
          Questions, suggestions, or critiques? Find me on the 
          <a href="/">main site</a>. Studio is an ongoing experiment. It will 
          evolve as I learn what works.
        </p>
      </section>
    </div>

    <footer class="about-footer">
      <div class="about-back">
        <a href="/studio" class="about-back-link">← Back to essays</a>
      </div>
    </footer>
  </article>

  <style>
    .about {
      max-width: 720px;
      margin: 0 auto;
    }

    .about-header {
      margin-bottom: var(--studio-space-16);
      padding-bottom: var(--studio-space-8);
      border-bottom: 1px solid var(--studio-border);
      opacity: 0;
      animation: fadeIn var(--studio-duration-slow) var(--studio-ease-out) forwards;
    }

    @keyframes fadeIn {
      from {
        opacity: 0;
        transform: translateY(20px);
      }
      to {
        opacity: 1;
        transform: translateY(0);
      }
    }

    .about-title {
      font-family: var(--studio-font-sans);
      font-size: var(--studio-text-4xl);
      font-weight: 600;
      letter-spacing: var(--studio-tracking-tight);
      line-height: var(--studio-leading-tight);
      color: var(--studio-text-primary);
      margin-bottom: var(--studio-space-4);
    }

    .about-subtitle {
      font-size: var(--studio-text-xl);
      color: var(--studio-text-muted);
      font-style: italic;
    }

    .about-content {
      opacity: 0;
      animation: fadeIn var(--studio-duration-slow) var(--studio-ease-out) 0.2s forwards;
    }

    .about-content section {
      margin-bottom: var(--studio-space-16);
    }

    .about-content section:last-of-type {
      margin-bottom: var(--studio-space-12);
    }

    .about-footer {
      margin-top: var(--studio-space-16);
      padding-top: var(--studio-space-8);
      border-top: 1px solid var(--studio-border);
    }

    .about-back-link {
      font-family: var(--studio-font-sans);
      font-size: var(--studio-text-sm);
      color: var(--studio-text-muted);
      text-decoration: none;
      letter-spacing: var(--studio-tracking-wide);
      transition: color var(--studio-duration-normal) var(--studio-ease-out);
      display: inline-flex;
      align-items: center;
      gap: var(--studio-space-2);
      border: none;
    }

    .about-back-link:hover {
      color: var(--studio-text-primary);
    }

    @media (max-width: 768px) {
      .about-title {
        font-size: var(--studio-text-3xl);
      }

      .about-subtitle {
        font-size: var(--studio-text-lg);
      }
    }

    @media (prefers-reduced-motion: reduce) {
      .about-header,
      .about-content {
        animation: none;
        opacity: 1;
      }
    }
  </style>
</StudioLayout>
